gement_10-Nov-2023.pdf%5C%22%3Ethe%20Supreme%20Court%20has%20ruled%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EArticle%20200%20of%20the%20constitution%20empowers%20governors%20to%20either%20give%20assent%20to%20passed%20Bills%2C%20withhold%20assent%2C%20or%20reserve%20them%20for%20the%20president%E2%80%99s%20consideration%20when%20he%20or%20she%20receives%20a%20Bill%20from%20the%20state%20government.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20apex%20court%20highlighted%20that%20the%20%E2%80%9Csubstantive%20part%20of%20Article%20200%20empowers%20the%20governor%20to%20withhold%20assent%20to%20the%20Bill%E2%80%9D%2C%20and%20that%20in%20such%20an%20event%2C%20the%20governor%20must%20communicate%20it%20to%20the%20State%20Legislature%20%E2%80%9Cas%20soon%20as%20possible%E2%80%9D%2C%20warranting%20the%20reconsideration%20of%20the%20Bill.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CThe%20expression%20%E2%80%9Cas%20soon%20as%20possible%E2%80%9D%20is%20significant.%20It%20conveys%20a%20constitutional%20imperative%20of%20expedition.%20Failure%20to%20take%20a%20call%20and%20keeping%20a%20Bill%20duly%20passed%20for%20indeterminate%20periods%20is%20a%20course%20of%20action%20inconsistent%20with%20that%20expression.%20Constitutional%20language%20is%20not%20surplusage%2C%E2%80%9D%20its%20judgment%20read.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIt%20further%20said%20that%20failing%20to%20read%20the%20governor%E2%80%99s%20power%20in%20Article%20200%20in%20this%20manner%20would%20put%20him%20in%20a%20%E2%80%9Cposition%20to%20virtually%20veto%E2%80%9D%20the%20elected%20legislature%E2%80%99s%20functioning.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9CSuch%20a%20course%20of%20action%20would%20be%20contrary%20to%20%5Bthe%5D%20fundamental%20principles%20of%20a%20constitutional%20democracy%20based%20on%20a%20parliamentary%20pattern%20of%20governance%2C%E2%80%9D%20it%20added.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAdditionally%2C%20the%20court%20said%20that%20governors%20are%20required%20to%20%E2%80%9Cdeclare%E2%80%9D%20which%20option%20they%20choose%20to%20exercise.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ETh